{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506068"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2514"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2514"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.45,0.16,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2514"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"1425"},{"type":"tags","id":"6040"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3495"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year old woman presents to the Emergency Department by ambulance with severe pain in her right hip after a fall. She thinks she fell over a loose cord across the dining room. Following the fall she was unable to get up off the floor and her husband called an ambulance. She has a medical history of osteoporosis. Her medications list includes alendronate and calcium supplements. She is very active, doing five kilometre walks most days and plays golf regularly. On musculoskeletal examination there is limited leg movement because of the pain and the right leg appears shortened and externally rotated. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hemiarthroplasty","Total arthroplasty","Intramedullary nail","Single sliding hip screw","Femoral head excision arthroplasty"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of considerations when planning conservative or surgical management of femoral hip fractures. Firstly, the majority of hip fractures patients are elderly and there needs to be consideration of their comorbidities in regard to their suitability for surgery. The best results are with surgical management and if safe to do so, the majority of patients will receive a form of surgical management.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main forms of intracapsular fracture management include internal fixation (either multiple cancellous screws or \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle sliding hip screw\u003C/strong\u003E), or arthroplasty (either hemi or total replacement). The choice depends on the degree of displacement (Garden stage) and comorbidities of the patient. The Garden classification\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eof femoral neck fractures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 1: valgus-impacted incomplete fracture and undisplaced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 2:  complete fracture and undisplaced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 3: complete fracture and partially displaced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 4: complete fracture and completely displaced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGarden state I/II are managed with internal fixation regardless of age. Generally, with patients under 65 it is best to aim for internal fixation as the arthroplasty may not last the patient\u2019s life expectancy and there is greater risk of re-intervention.\u00a0 Garden III/IV\u00a0 and older than 65 are usually managed with either \u003Cstrong\u003Ehemi or total hip arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E. The decision between hemiarthroplasty and total is controversial and can be very patient dependant. Some factors that may push the clinician towards using a total hip replacement include good pre-fracture mobility, and no cognitive impairment.\u00a0This patient is 65-years-old, in good health and mobility; and has suffered an intracapsular fracture making a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A total arthroplasty is the recommended treatment for an intracapsular fracture in a fit and healthy individual."],"references":["Callaghan JJ, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surgical Br. 2012;94:19-21. Available at: https://boneandjoint.org.uk/article/10.1302/0301-620X.94B11.30617","Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017;377:2053-62. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1611090"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2514"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1855"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1855"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6bcc9b7-2a17-4117-8652-0b6c4fc15142.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6bcc9b7-2a17-4117-8652-0b6c4fc15142.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":658}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63425","lin